description.text:
I made this to be a 9mm OD washer with a 4.25mm ID hole and 1.5mm thickness, for use as replacements/additionals for the Robo 3D extruder tension screws. The reality of it is that it printed for me at a snug 4mm (still getting my head around inflation), but that actually turned out to be a mad bonus. They actually thread on easily and don't fly off when you let go of the compressed springs - the threads keep them caged to the bolts. Oh happy day; now I don't have to chase washers all over the house every time I slip and let one of the tension screws fly free. Now I can have as many or as few washers on the bolts to better play with filament tension, and my success can now be yours! B-)

In The Photo - Yeah baby, that's aluminum under them washers! :-).

Printer:

Notes:

Although I designed this for use for the Robo 3D tension screws, they make a good generic washer for a lot of things. Stretch the height, width, depth to suit your needs. Printed in PETG or ABS, they'll take a lot of abuse, but you can also print in PLA for less abusive ends, just watch that they will never have to get hot or you'll have gaskets in no time, lol. These print godawful fast at 0.2mm, so I strongly reccomend printing a bunch at once to prevent globbing/warping during print (each gets a chance to cool). I printed 36 of them at once on my first attempt, and they all came out beautifully in actually slightly less than a minute each, 35 minutes total. I'll never want for a plastic washer again, THANK YOU ROBO 3D!

Oh, one last thing. I print with Simplify 3D and each time I load this, it complains about the part being very small and perhaps in inches format. Perhaps NOT. If you get such a warning, asking you if you want to change the format, DON'T. Let it load without changes, and it will work fine as intended.

The Elves were on vacay so I took over in the R&D Dept. I slipped with a tiny Elf donut, and it bumped together with a piece of filament, and presto, a tiny plastic disc was born. I thought, "Wow... This is really tragic, I'm out of donuts now and I'll never have any use for this disaster of a part!" Then I slipped up with my tension screw on my Robo 3D, lost a metal washer and grabbed the first thing I could find - the Plastic Mini Elf Donut, or PMED for short. It worked so well that I eventually changed the name to "Washer".

I'm kidding. I'm just having a REALLY bad week with the printer. Made this in a desperate attempt to get somewhere with it.

Its a mousetrap derived from the venus fly trap. The principle is simple: Mouse steps on a plate, mouse falls down in the chamber, the trap closes above the mouse, thus trapping the mouse inside.

The picture is from a facebook game called mousehunt.
For added realism, add something that can dissolve mice

Print the 3 pieces. They should not be bigger than 8x8x8cm in size. Use some glue and paper, or elastic bands, to make sure that the trap stays on top. A typical mouse weighs around 10-25g, so make sure that the paper rips as soon as the mouse steps on the plates. I would recommend eating paper. Put some smelly cheese in the middle and the rest should explain itself.

title: Secretly Locking Seafall Treasure Chest
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
My gaming group got Seafall with the intent to play it, and I was looking at the terribly boring cardboard treasure chests that came with it, and I just felt the need to do something more fun, and although I originally planned to secure the lid with magnets, I got carried away and made it have a secret locking mechanism where you rotate the symbol on the top and it locks and unlocks.

I've only finished one of the Seafall symbols so far as I've just finished the prototype build, but I've included a blank symbol part if you want to stick your own thing on it.

Both brimmed and unbrimmed parts included as the PLA I was printing was lifting up at the corners a little. The symbol will probably need a little sanding around the edges so it fits just right.

Rotate so the bottom is down on all parts when printing... My cad program works 90 degrees to everything else...

Needs about 4 spots of glue to attach the lid parts together and another to glue the logo disc on.

Open stl file in Tinkercad

Download the vector graphic that you like
Log on to http://www.selva3d.com/ and upload your chosen vector graphic
Download the free version of the resulting stl file
Import the stl file into your Tinkercad file
Resize and arrange the top to your liking. Make the height of the object 4.5.
Download your stl file from Tinkercad

description.text:
Hanging repurposed bottles for the window farm project can be challenging.  If your chain or rope or zip-ties are not perfectly 180 degrees apart, your bottle will hang crooked.
The bottle hammock is a 4th generation idea for hanging repurposed bottles.  The simple design helps ensure that your hanging string is 180 degrees apart.  The two ring system supports the bottom of the upside down bottle on the neck and balances anywhere in the middle.

• Measure your bottle and print one set. Adjust the SCAD file if necessary. The 2.5 inch set is for evian and nestle bottles. The 3 inch set can be used for ice mountain and larger bottles.
  • The part with the groove on half is the support ring, this goes on the neck of the overturned bottle.
  • The part with the holes is the balance ring, this goes higher up on the bottle to keep it from tipping over. You can support this ring with two zip-ties on the bottle so it doesn't slide down. Tension from the strings that hang it keep it in place fairly well without zip ties.
  • Place the support ring on the bottom of a loop of string.
  • Place the neck of the bottle in the support ring.
  • Slide the balance ring over the top of the bottle.
  • Place the string into the side holes of the balance ring.
  • Clip your hair hose into the air hose holder.
  • Hang the string above a window.

title: Shaft for Opel Astra H defective Recirculation system

description.text:
This part is designed for fixing the recurring fault of the recirculating system on Opel Astra H caused by excessive torque of the servo onto the internal flap (plastic part cracks).

The reason for failure (imho) is the combination of constructive miscalculation of materials and excessive torque.

A defective flap has a low response speed, can not tightly closes the external air flow and consequently smell / pollution passes easily into the car.

Guides for replacing or fixing the defective flap are also availabe by google search.

A 50 to 120 ohm resistor (2W) in series to the motor is necessary in order to prevent further faults.

Printer:

HelloBeePrusa

Rafts:

No

Yes

0.2 - 0.3

100%

I printed it with PLA, with shaft in vertical position.
